issue.title: MaxUnpool indices incompatible with PyTorch and inconsistent with MaxPool for kernels sizes which aren't a multiple of output size

repository.name: onnx
repository.description: Open standard for machine learning interoperability

issue.body:
## Summary
ONNX's [`MaxUnpool-11`](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Changelog.md#MaxUnpool-11) indexing is incompatible with PyTorch's MaxUnpool for kernel sizes which aren't a multiple of the output size. ONNX MaxUnpool is even incompatible with ONNX's own [`MaxPool-11`](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Changelog.md#MaxPool-11) for such cases, as MaxPool outputs indices as a large 1D tensor agnostic to padding or kernel size/stride (consistent with PyTorch) whereas MaxUnpool seems to be doing something weird related to the inferred output shape and ignoring the explicitly specified `output_shape`. So feeding MaxPool's indices output onward to MaxUnpool gives gibberish results since they map to the wrong element offsets (or worse, [fail to execute the model](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2154)).

The backend example `with_output_shape` should fix indices `xI` to the following:

``` python
node = onnx.helper.make_node(
    'MaxUnpool',
    inputs=['xT', 'xI', 'output_shape'],
    outputs=['y'],
    kernel_shape=[2, 2],
    strides=[2, 2]
)
xT = np.array([[[[5, 6],
                 [7, 8]]]], dtype=np.float32)
# From:
# xI = np.array([[[[5, 7],
#                 [13, 15]]]], dtype=np.int64)
# To:
xI = np.array([[[[6, 8], # Corrected values
                 [16, 18]]]], dtype=np.int64)
output_shape = np.array((1, 1, 5, 5), dtype=np.int64)
y = np.array([[[[0, 0, 0, 0, 0],
                [0, 5, 0, 6, 0],
                [0, 0, 0, 0, 0],
                [0, 7, 0, 8, 0],
                [0, 0, 0, 0, 0]]]], dtype=np.float32)
expect(node, inputs=[xT, xI, output_shape], outputs=[y], name='test_maxunpool_export_with_output_shape')
```

The indices given in the example only make sense if `output_shape` is 4x4.

## Further explanation
[`MaxPool-11`](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Changelog.md#MaxPool-11) finds maximal values in the unpooled input tensor and outputs indices of the maximal values selected, where indices are 0-based offsets pointing into the input tensor as if it was a huge 1D tensor (per spec, padding is irrelevant to this index value) with index values ranging `[0, N x C x D1 x ... x Dn)`. "The indices are computed as flatten 1-D tensor, and the indices do not consider padding."

[`MaxUnpool-11`](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Changelog.md#MaxUnpool-11) then reads those maximal values and indices (tensor output from `MaxPool`), restoring the maximal values to their element offsets in the unpooled output tensor (which has the same size and type as the corresponding original input tensor to `MaxPool`) and writing zeros to all other values in the output.

These two operators are roughly symmetric in that the output of one reverses the other. So calling `MaxUnpool(MaxPool(...))` yields the original input tensor (for the maximal elements anyway, leaving other elements zero), and the reverse composition `MaxPool(MaxUnpool(...))` returns output identical to the input tensor.

For pooling cases where the kernel evenly fits into the MaxUnpool output, there is no discrepancy between ONNX MaxPool/MaxUnpool (matches PyTorch). For odd sizes where the kernel doesn't even fit evenly, and the inferred shape differs from the actual full shape (e.g. 5x5 with 2x2 kernel and 2x2 strides), ONNX MaxPool is compatible with PyTorch (and yields the expected indices), but ONNX MaxUnpool is not - even when you pass the correct `output_shape` to MaxUnpool, since it appears ONNX MaxUnpool is bewilderingly using the inferred output shape (4x4) for indexing rather than the actual shape passed to it (5x5). So, values end up being written back to the wrong elements.

Now, there _is_ a potential ambiguity with MaxUnpool's output tensor size since more than one possible input tensor size to MaxPool reduces to the same output tensor size (e.g. MaxPool maps both a 2x2 and a 3x3 input tensor to 1x1 output, when given a 2x2 kernel and 2x2 stride), but all the examples below use `output_shape` explicitly, and so this is not the issue - the issue is the indexing.

## Example case
The original example is a 5x5 input, but we can simplify the example even more to use 3x3 input with 2x2 kernel and 2x2 strides:

### Code

``` python
import torch;

pool = torch.nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, return_indices=True)
unpool = torch.nn.MaxUnpool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
    
original_input = torch.tensor(
                    [[[[0, 0, 0],
                       [3, 0, 0],
                       [0, 0, 0]]]],
                    dtype=torch.float32
                    );
    
pooled_values, indices = pool(original_input)
unpooled = unpool(pooled_values, indices, output_size=torch.Size([1, 1, 3, 3]))

print("original_input:\n", original_input, sep='')
print("maxpool_output:\n", pooled_values, sep='')
print("maxpool_indices:\n", indices, sep='')
print("maxunpool_output:\n", unpooled, sep='')
print()
```

``` json
    {
      "op_type": "MaxPool",
      "version": 8,
      "kernel_shape": [2, 2],
      "pads": [0,0, 0,0],
      "strides": [2,2],
      "storage_order": 0,
      "X":       [[[[ 0, 0, 0],
                    [ 3, 0, 0],
                    [ 0, 0, 0]]]],
      "Y":       [[[[ 3]]]],
      "indices": [[[[ 3]]]],
      "T": "float32"
    },
    {
      "op_type": "MaxUnpool",
      "version": 9,
      "kernel_shape": [2, 2],
      "strides": [2, 2],
      "X": [[[[3]]]],
      "I": [[[[ 3]]]],
      "output_shape": [1, 1, 3, 3],
      "Y": [[[[0, 0, 0],
              [3, 0, 0], // <- expected
              [0, 0, 0]]]],
      "T1": "float32"
    }
```

### Output

PyTorch output:
``` python
tensor([[[[0., 0., 0.], # original values (MaxPool input)
          [3., 0., 0.],
          [0., 0., 0.]]]])
tensor([[[[3.]]]]) # maximal value
tensor([[[[3]]]]) # indices output
tensor([[[[0., 0., 0.], # MaxUnpool output (matches MaxPool input)
          [3., 0., 0.],
          [0., 0., 0.]]]])
```

ONNX output:
``` python
tensor([[[[0., 0., 0.], # original values (MaxPool input)
          [3., 0., 0.],
          [0., 0., 0.]]]])
tensor([[[[3.]]]]) # maximal value
tensor([[[[3]]]]) # indices output
tensor([[[[0., 0., 0.], # MaxUnpool output (should match MaxPool input)
          [0., 3., 0.], <-- mismatched!
          [0., 0., 0.]]]])
```

## Proposed fix 
Make MaxUnpool use the same indexing as MaxPool, just like how MaxPool treats the indices purely as offsets within the unpooled tensor (regardless of padding or strides or kernel size). *The reverse alternative would be to make MaxPool's indexing compatible with MaxUnpool, but then ONNX MaxPool would be incompatible with PyTorch which hampers interop.

issue.title: Fix MaxUnpool behaviour when output_shape is provided and doesn't match the inferred shape

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 
MaxUnpool should reconstitute what was pooled by MaxPool. The kernel_shape, pads and strides inputs are purely to infer an output shape, if output_shape is not explicitly provided. 

The unpool should not be adding new padding, so output_shape is not about auto generating pad values and inserting pads.

The current ORT implementation misinterprets the usage of output_shape and inserts pads instead of just allocating an output of the specified shape, and directly unpooling into it.

Update to simply find the correct output shape to use, and simply unpool into that.

Update unit tests to reflect this.

**Motivation and Context**
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2398
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2154
